You can be assured that we won\u2019t tolerate this kind of behavior and any future instances that might occur that are similar to this won\u2019t be allowed to serve in the company,\u201d Alampay said.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e The employee who took the video was also sanctioned, the executives added.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e \u201cVideo-taking is restricted in any of our facilities, not only for the protection of our workers but first and foremost for the protection of our parcels as well. So this is a direct violation of company standard procedure,\u201d Alampay explained.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Even media personnel invited to tour one of the company\u2019s warehouses were not allowed to bring cameras inside.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e  \\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cblockquote class=\\\"twitter-tweet\\\"\\u003e \\u003cp dir=\\\"ltr\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\\u003e Signs like this one are all over the J&T Express warehouse. They have been tagged appropriately. And they have already reached their intended destination. We have received no formal complaints coming from any of the customers or recipients of those parcels,\u201d Alampay added.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e President Rodrigo Duterte ordered an investigation into J&T Express and had threatened to close down the company.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e When asked if they will seek a dialogue with the president, Alampay replied, \u201cWe don\u2019t believe that any dialogue is necessary because again, any action that they take to investigate the incident is something we believe is concordant with their duty to protect public interest and to protect consumer rights. So this is a direct violation of company standard procedure,\u201d Alampay explained.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Even media personnel invited to tour one of the company\u2019s warehouses were not allowed to bring cameras inside.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e  \\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cblockquote class=\\\"twitter-tweet\\\"\\u003e \\u003cp dir=\\\"ltr\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\\u003e Signs like this one are all over the J&T Express warehouse. We were shocked to see the video. We humbly take full responsibility for this incident,\u201d she said.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Chi added that J&T Express has embarked on reforms, including creating a new quality control team, retraining their employees, and compensating affected customers.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e But J&T Express branding manager Leonardo Alampay insisted that the incident is an isolated case and is contrary to company standards.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Alampay said they have a system in place that can track every parcel and identify all employees who handle it.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Alampay added that their warehouses and offices are also equipped with CCTV cameras, which also helped them identify everyone in the viral video.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e \u201cThe people involved in the video are on-call riders and sorters temporarily hired by the company. You can be assured that we won\u2019t tolerate this kind of behavior and any future instances that might occur that are similar to this won\u2019t be allowed to serve in the company,\u201d Alampay said.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e The employee who took the video was also sanctioned, the executives added.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e \u201cVideo-taking is restricted in any of our facilities, not only for the protection of our workers but first and foremost for the protection of our parcels as well. So this is a direct violation of company standard procedure,\u201d Alampay explained.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Even media personnel invited to tour one of the company\u2019s warehouses were not allowed to bring cameras inside.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e  \\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cblockquote class=\\\"twitter-tweet\\\"\\u003e \\u003cp dir=\\\"ltr\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\\u003e Signs like this one are all over the J&T Express warehouse. They have been tagged appropriately. And they have already reached their intended destination. We have received no formal complaints coming from any of the customers or recipients of those parcels,\u201d Alampay added.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e President Rodrigo Duterte ordered an investigation into J&T Express and had threatened to close down the company.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e When asked if they will seek a dialogue with the president, Alampay replied, \u201cWe don\u2019t believe that any dialogue is necessary because again, any action that they take to investigate the incident is something we believe is concordant with their duty to protect public interest and to protect consumer rights. So we think that this investigation, if they find it necessary, we will find it necessary as well to better improve our services.\u201d\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e There are also photos circulating online allegedly taken inside a J&T Express warehouse where packages were haphazardly dumped and have almost reached the ceiling, and where shirtless workers could be seen lying down on the packages.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Alampay said the photos were old and that the issue had been resolved.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e \u201cRegardless of how they might be portrayed in social media, they are all organized and effectively sorted according to the areas that we intend to deliver them,\u201d Alampay assured.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e \u201cAny parcel that is lost, no matter how improbable that might be regarding the system that we are using, they can be compensated for justly and fairly through our claims system,\u201d he added. \\u003cstrong\\u003e\u2014 BM, GMA You can be assured that we won\u2019t tolerate this kind of behavior and any future instances that might occur that are similar to this won\u2019t be allowed to serve in the company,\u201d Alampay said.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e The employee who took the video was also sanctioned, the executives added.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e \u201cVideo-taking is restricted in any of our facilities, not only for the protection of our workers but first and foremost for the protection of our parcels as well. So this is a direct violation of company standard procedure,\u201d Alampay explained.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e Even media personnel invited to tour one of the company\u2019s warehouses were not allowed to bring cameras inside.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e  \\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cblockquote class=\\\"twitter-tweet\\\"\\u003e \\u003cp dir=\\\"ltr\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\\u003e Signs like this one are all over the J&T Express warehouse. and at the moment that&#39;s been the \\u003cbr\\u003e\\n\\u003cb\\u003eexpress\\u003c/b\\u003e parcels companies,\u201d says John Manners-Bell, chief&nbsp;...\",\n      \"formattedUrl\": \"https://www.ft.com/content/392e7cd2-90e6-11e4-914a-00144feabdc0\",\n      \"htmlFormattedUrl\": \"https://www.ft.com/content/392e7cd2-90e6-11e4-914a-00144feabdc0\",\n      \"pagemap\": {\n        \"cse_thumbnail\": [\n          {\n            \"src\": \"https://encrypted-tbn2.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcRr6xWgNnKX8fc_j6gUF4Gifghw69RF2MeSZu8JniHz2UIFjr13bTSIH04\",\n            \"width\": \"300\",\n            \"height\": \"168\"\n          }\n        ],\n        \"NewsArticle\": [\n          {\n            \"datePublished\": \"2015-01-04T21:08:45Z\",\n            \"alternativeHeadline\": \"City Link collapse shows systemic problems\",\n            \"itemtype\": \"http://schema.org/NewsArticle\",\n            \"wordCount\": \"972\",\n            \"articleBody\": \"The collapse of City Link on New Year\u2019s Eve has opened a window into the true costs of parcel delivery in the online shopping era.\\n\\nRecord levels of internet spending in the run up to Christmas were not enough to save the lossmaking business, which had not delivered a profit in more than five years.\\n\\nBetter Capital, the private equity turnround specialist that bought the ailing business from Rentokil for just \u00a31 last year, blamed City Link\u2019s collapse on \u201cmassive overcapacity in the market which is driving down prices\u201d, adding that trade was being cannibalised by retailers such as Amazon taking more of their delivery operations in-house.\\n\\nAs a result, the courier company found itself being driven into Britain\u2019s low-wage economy. Many of its competitors rely on self-employed migrant workers in hired vans, working long hours to make deliveries for as little as 45p per package, depending on size, weight and delivery radius.\\n\\nBetter Capital put City Link workers on fresh contracts when it took over the company, paying drivers on a per-parcel basis, which drove it into conflict with trade unions. But it was unable to stem its losses.\\n\\nAt base is what one of City Link\u2019s competitors has dubbed the \u201cAmazon-isation\u201d of the delivery industry \u2014 online consumers expect rapid, traceable and conveniently timed deliveries as standard but do not want to pay much for the service.\\n\\nRetailers have been loath to absorb the cost either and with around 10 established delivery companies competing for their business, they have not needed to.\\n\\n\u201cSomebody has to pay for that \u2018free shipping\u2019 and at the moment that\u2019s been the express parcels companies,\u201d says John Manners-Bell, chief executive of Transport Intelligence, the consultancy firm. He says some parcels companies have been slashing their rates in a bid to capture more business.\\n\\nCommentators agree that City Link was forced to offer \u201csub-market pricing\u201d to win contracts, fuelling a cycle of unsustainable losses.\\n\\nRetailers \u201cput a lot of negotiating pressure on the carriers, the carriers respond to it, but of course when they fail the carriers get vilified. It\u2019s all a bit of a vicious circle,\u201d says Alan Braithwaite, chairman of LCP Consulting.\\n\\nIT costs put further pressure on the delivery companies, because internet shoppers expect to be able to track their parcels online. Some of City Link\u2019s rivals started adding services such as a \u201c30-minute warning\u201d text to customers waiting for deliveries, putting the company further on the back foot.\\n\\n\u201cThese guys add costs faster than they make profit,\u201d says Mr Braithwaite.\\n\\nThe wider industry has responded by slashing costs. Instead of employing drivers as full-time employees, most courier firms rely on self-employed drivers who rent their vans, company uniform and radios and are paid on a per-parcel basis.\\n\\nThe practice is standard throughout the industry, according to Mr Manners-Bell. \u201cIt is the only way these companies can really work because there are lots of peaks and troughs throughout the year and you need to be able to bring people on as and when they are required,\u201d he said.\\n\\nAs a result, the \u201cWhite Van Man\u201d who once dominated the courier trade has driven off, to be replaced by migrant workers from eastern Europe, Latin America and northern Africa who \u2014 armed with a Sat Nav \u2014 are having to work gruelling hours to make back their costs.\\n\\nOne employee of a large London-based delivery company estimates that only one in 10 of its van drivers are British nationals.\\n\\n\u201cOur fleet of white van men are ageing and diminishing in number. Most drivers are Brazilian, Hungarian or Nigerian,\u201d he says. \u201cThe more experienced guys will have accountants, but I would say the majority don\u2019t pay any income tax. All we\u2019re interested in is whether they have courier insurance.\u201d\\n\\nFounded in 1969 to provide a road transfer service for British Rail\u2019s Red Star Parcels, City Link evolved into a national logistics operation headquartered in the West Midlands \u201cGolden Triangle\u201d where the M1, M6 and M42 motorways intersect, and 98 per cent of the UK population can be accessed within a four-hour drive.\\n\\nRentokil acquired City Link in 1993 and merged the business with Target Express in 2007 \u2014 a drawn-out process complicated by incompatible IT systems, management disputes and board departures.\\n\\nIndustry veteran Petar Cvetkovic was then Target\u2019s chief executive and later went on to become City Link\u2019s managing director. He now runs Aim-listed delivery rival DX Group, which works with customers who value security and reliability, predominantly serving B2B customers and delivering higher-value items such as passports and bank cards in the B2C market.\\n\\n\u201cIn the consumer market, delivery companies who can\u2019t differentiate themselves have gone down the \u2018stack \u2018em high, sell it cheap\u2019 business model where deliveries can be thrown onto doorsteps,\u201d he says. \u201cCity Link were selling at low end prices that could not support their cost structure.\u201d\\n\\nMr Cvetkovic says that overcapacity issues stem from an annual problem \u2014 demand for delivery services always shoots up in the last two months of the year. In the Christmas of 2008, he \u201ccapped\u201d the number of parcels that City Link would deliver for major retailers to maintain a quality of service and to avoid the service meltdowns that have plagued rival operator Yodel during the festive season. \u201cWarehouses don\u2019t have rubber walls that expand,\u201d he says.\\n\\nCity Link\u2019s failure will take some capacity out of an overcrowded market, but more is being added \u2014 Royal Mail, DPD and Hermes are all building new delivery hubs. Retailers are steering online customers towards \u201cclick and collect\u201d that allows them to deliver goods more efficiently to stores.\\n\\n\u201cPeople haven\u2019t worked out the best operating models,\u201d says Mr Manners-Bell.\",\n            \"description\": \"Overcapacity in the market is driving down prices, making profitability difficult\",\n            \"dateModified\": Condor, a charter carrier for tourists, will operate four of its Boeing 767 medium-size jets for DHL until the end of May. The Condor planes will be based at DHL Express\u2019 largest European hub in Leipzig, Germany and cover three routes - to Shannon, Ireland; Milan-Malpensa, Italy; and Cologne, Germany. DHL suggested the initial contract could be extended.\\n\\n\\n\\nIt\u2019s the latest example of smaller passenger airlines diversifying business amid a severe downturn in travel demand and establishing full cargo divisions for the first time. The Condor deal resembles what DHL has done in the U.S. where regional carrier Mesa Air Group in October began flying converted Boeing 737-400s, an aircraft it never operated before, on DHL\u2019s behalf. \\n\\n\\n\\nAir Belgium is scheduled to begin operating four Airbus A-330 owned by ocean carrier CMA CGM - taking the concept of diversification to another level. And U.S. low-cost travel airline Sun Country last year began operating 737-800 freighters for Amazon Air.\\n\\n\\n\\n\u201cThis partnership between cargo and passenger carriers is unique,\u201d said Markus Otto, senior vice president aviation Europe at DHL Express, in a statement. \u201cIt allows us to react even faster and more flexibly to the continued high demand for international express service. The additional capacity through Condor allows us to further improve service quality and transit times, and maintain our growth trajectory.\u201d\\n\\n\\n\\nSince April of last year, Condor, like many passenger airlines, has emphasized cargo flights, transporting primarily medical protective equipment and e-commerce goods. At one point, 14 of Condor\u2019s 16 Boeing 767 aircraft were being used solely for cargo. Condor has also trained and deployed a team of cargo supervisors to oversee cargo operations and ensure quality execution. \\n\\n\\n\\nSmartLynx\\n\\n\\n\\nIn-house airline DHL Aviation also hired SmartLynx Malta, a new cargo subsidiary of Riga, Latvia-based SmartLynx Airlines, that is one of the earliest adopters of the new Airbus A321 converted freighter. \\n\\n\\n\\nAn Airbus A321 passenger plane owned by Vallair at a maintenance shop where major renovations are done to make it a full-time freighter. Vallair is leasing the plane to SmartLynx Malta, which will then operate it on a dedicated basis for DHL Aviation. (Photo: Vallair)\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nSmartLynx Malta has leased two of the narrowbody planes and will begin operating the first one for DHL at the end of March, DHL spokesman Tim Rehkopf said. The second aircraft is still being retrofitted and will join the DHL fleet by mid-July.\\n\\n\\n\\nSmartLynx is moving aggressively to establish its cargo division, with plans to add eight more of the well-regarded A321 freighters by 2023.\\n\\n\\n\\nThe first two A321 passenger-to-freighter conversions so far are seeing duty with Qantas/Australia Post and Titan Airways. \\n\\n\\n\\nAviation experts say the A321 is an excellent choice for regional and express delivery operators because it has more cargo space for containers than the 737-800, its main competition, and its fuel efficiency over older aircraft.\\n\\n\\n\\nThe A321 is \u201cgoing to be a great freighter,\u201d said Stan Wraight, CEO a;nd co-founder of Strategic Aviation Solutions, in a video chat for Global Supply Chain Week at FreightWaves.\\n\\n\\n\\nFounded in 1992, SmartLynx is part of Avia Solutions Group, a large aerospace services company with businesses ranging from aircraft leasing to maintenance and repair. One of Avia\u2019s cargo subsidiaries is charter airline Magma Aviation. SmartLynx has extensive experience operating the A320 and A321 as a passenger charter operator and provider of air transport for airline customers.\\n\\n\\n\\nSmartlynx Malta says it plans to add two more  A321 freighters this year and up to four units during 2022, with the goal of becoming one of the largest narrow-body cargo freight carriers within the next three years.\\n\\n\\n\\nIn January, DHL Express ordered eight 777 freighters from Boeing as part of its effort to keep up with growing cargo volumes. \\n\\n\\n\\nClick here for more FreightWaves/American Shipper stories by Eric Kulisch.\\n\\n\\n\\nRELATED NEWS:\\n\\n\\n\\nWhy the A321 freighter looks like a hot ticket\\n\\n\\n\\nTitan to operate world\u2019s second A321 converted freighter\\n\\n\\n\\nAEI receives large order for 737-800 converted freighters\\n\\n\\n\\nShipping line CMA CGM\u2019s first air cargo destination: Chicago\\n\\n\\n\\nOcean carrier CMA CGM buys jets for new air cargo unit\\n\\n\\n\\nMesa Airlines makes first cargo flight for DHL\",\n            \"copyrightYear\": \"2021\",\n            \"name\": \"DHL Express gets creative with new aviation partnerships\",\n            \"description\": \"DHL Express last week made two unusual additions to its roster of contract carriers that bring with them extra aircraft to help the parcel carrier meet escalating growth in e-commerce shipments.
